{% extends "layouts/main.twig" %}

{% block full_width_content %}{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
<div class="text-center py-12">
    <span class="text-xs font-bold tracking-widest dark:text-slate-700 uppercase bg-indigo-300 px-3 py-1 rounded-full border border-indigo-500">
        Biblical Commentary Series
    </span>
    <h1 class="text-5xl font-bold text-gray-800 dark:text-white tracking-tight mt-6" style="font-size: 48px;">Abortion</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-2xl mx-auto text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
        A commentary on the controversial topic of abortion.
    </p>
</div>

<div class="mt-8 border-t dark:border-gray-700 pt-12">
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3">What does the Bible say?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-4">
        The Bible does not use the phrase "once saved, always saved". It is one of the most debated topics in Christianity, with scriptural arguments supporting both sides.
    </p>
    <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3">1. Arguments Supporting Eternal Security</h4>

        <p>Proponents of this view believe that once a person is truly saved, God guarantees their eternal destiny. They emphasize that salvation is a permanent gift of God's grace, not something earned or maintained by human effort.</p>

        <p>
            <strong>Romans 8:38-39:</strong> The Apostle Paul declares that nothing in all creation "will be able to separate us from the love of God that is in Christ Jesus our Lord". <br>
            <strong>John 10:28-29:</strong> Jesus promises regarding His followers, "I give them eternal life, and they shall never perish; no one will snatch them out of my hand". <br>
            <strong>Ephesians 1:13-14:</strong> Believers are described as being "sealed with the promised Holy Spirit," which acts as a guarantee of their inheritance.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3 mt-3">2. Arguments Against Eternal Security</h4>

        <p>Opponents of "once saved, always saved" believe it is possible for a believer to voluntarily turn away from Christ, lose their faith, and forfeit their salvation. They stress the necessity of faithfully enduring to the end.</p>
        <p>
            <strong>Hebrews 6:4-6:</strong> This passage warns that it is "impossible to bring back to repentance" those who have once shared in the Holy Spirit but then "fall away."<br>
            <strong>Matthew 10:22:</strong> Jesus explicitly states, "The one who stands firm to the end will be saved".<br>
            <strong>Philippians 2:12:</strong> Paul instructs believers to "continue to work out your salvation with fear and trembling," implying a responsibility to maintain one's faith.<br>
            <strong>Romans 11:22:</strong> Paul warns the grafted-in Gentiles that they, too, will be "cut off" if they do not continue in God's kindness.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-3 mt-3">Reconciling the Views</h4>

        <p>Many theologians suggest that these passages work together: God's grace is absolute and secure, but true, saving faith will always result in a persevering relationship with God. From this perspective, a believer who completely abandons the faith gives evidence that their original profession may not have been genuine, or that they have not truly accepted Christ.</p>
    </div>
</div>
{% endblock %}